english:
  title: Blue Words for the Ceremony Honoring Young Prince's Original Name
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The first offering comes as the Six Stems complete their circle—the moment when Young Prince receives his mandate. With singular devotion, we perform the rites of sincerity before the High Lord. Duckweed and water plants may suffice as offerings, yet millet and grain lack their fragrance.

    The second offering—unseen, unknowable—who can fathom the work of creation itself? Yet feeling reaches through, and we beg for the grace of illumination from above. Boldly we make our declaration: may you descend and accept this pure sacrifice.

    At the third offering: Heaven shows favor to the virtuous without partiality—thus the Mandate is not easily held. A father cherishes his son through loving kindness—such is the heart's nature. We reflect deeply: the Heir Apparent has inherited the great work, yet in humble deference has remained silent and reverent. We fear lest worry cloud the harmony we seek to preserve.

    Today we choose an auspicious hour and offer this spotless ceremony. Deign to descend and accept the wine we raise. Let the sincerity of our hearts endure, that all may flourish in filial harmony. Grant prosperity and longevity, that blessings may flow eternal.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a ceremonial address (cheong sa, 청사) written for a naming ceremony (醮 醮, jiao). Such texts were composed to accompany ritual offerings and invoke divine blessing and protection.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Young Prince' (小王) likely refers to a royal heir or young nobleman receiving his formal name. In Korean court tradition, such ceremonies were important rites of passage.
  - key: ''
    value: The references to 'Six Stems' (육갑) and 'auspicious hours' reflect the traditional Chinese calendrical system used in East Asian court rituals.
